Foods to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the euro area is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 countries of the Eurozone, inflation was higher than expected in November - after 2.6% in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1% was recorded, according to the Statistical Office of the EU in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, British, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the benchmark interest rate. Judging by the rise in commodity prices and the slight decline in unemployment, the lowering of the benchmark interest rate would favor the emergence of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB seeks to keep inflation below 2%, or at least close to the 2% mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in a quandary: inflation must be "agreed" in order to exclude the need for further action.
At 3.3 percent in November, the inflation rate in Germany reached a record twelve years; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The rise in inflation in the euro area is attributable to higher food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat quotes rose 88%, and the soybean price also reached a record high since 1973.
Edible oil and dairy products also experienced substantial inflation in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached almost 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1% to 2.5% in 2008, but is expected to fall to 1.9% in 2009.
Analysts expect a 3 percent inflation rate for the next three months, but put the annual average rate at 2.1 percent.
Experts expect the ECB to lower interest rates twice in 2008.
Gallup detects government crisis
After a long period of stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz has grown considerably until the beginning of December. For the first time since 2002, the party has the largest base camp, while support for the Socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
The difference among the party ’ s loyal voters is clear, thanks to the strong determination of the opposition ’ s supporters: more than two-thirds (71%) oppose a fifth (20%) of support for the MSZP.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary threshold: they account for two percent of the total population.
The number of party voters in both camps has grown by one percent.
Compared to the last low, the general economic sentiment has further deteriorated - never before has the proportion of those who consider the economic situation of the country to be "extremely bad" been so high (41 percent), while another 46 percent consider it to be "quite bad".
After more hopeful prospects in the spring and summer, families are seeing the change in their financial situation once again more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects a further deterioration of the situation; only a tenth expects an improvement.
A Gallup poll conducted in December found that 71% of respondents - a historic high - rated the Prime Minister's work as "rather bad than right."
Thirteen percent of respondents have great confidence or trust in Ferenc Gyurcsány in general, while the proportion of supporters of Viktor Orbán is 38 percent.
About 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared with 27% distrust of the party leader of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of people who think that dissatisfaction with the prime minister can be addressed without a change of government.
After last October ’ s riots, 35% said they wanted the government and the head of government to stay, but today this figure is only 20%, while the relative majority (33%) sees the solution only in new elections.
When asked about their interest in the referendum, 60% answered that they would "certainly" participate, and another 20% would "probably" vote.
By way of comparison: if the parliamentary elections were to take place on this Sunday, only 55 per cent would go to the polls "with certainty", and another 15 per cent consider their participation "likely". In view of these tendencies, the result of the referendum would be foreseeable.
74% would vote against the tuition fees, 79% against the practice fees, and 84% against the hospital fees.
Applied to the group of the referendum "with security" participants the portions of the opponents of the study, practice and hospital fees would amount to as much as 81, 84, and / or 89 per cent.
Most expensive, Tesco increased by almost a fifth
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs trading area maintained the average price increase of 16% from last year, with the difference that there was no VAT increase this year.
Article from Napi Gazdaság
In the Budaörs trading triangle, the price of the usual Christmas basket of the "Napi" has again increased by 16 percent this year, although price increases of over 1,000 HUF have been registered in all hypermarkets.
After the prices in the food markets "davongaloppiert" last December, the inflation did not turn out drastic proportionally, compared with the already high, earlier starting level.
However, it certainly has a deterrent effect on consumers that what they paid for last year far below 9,000 HUF is not even available for 10,000 HUF this year.
The price of the "Napi" shopping cart exceeded the magic 10,000 HUF threshold by at least 91 HUF in the markets examined.
The highest price was HUF 10,573.
(In 6800 the price was 6.800 HUF.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish remained almost at the previous year ’ s level, while prices for turkey breast fillets, nuts and poppy seeds rose sharply.
Prices for flour and bread corresponded to the data of the Central Statistical Office of Hungary, with Auchan however there were 1kg bread roasts for 139 forints.
There was no competitive fall in product prices below 200 HUF.
Also surprising was the price of a two liter Coca Cola deposit bottle of less than 200 Forint, so the drink including deposit cost only 257 HUF.
Nevertheless, this year in the "Napi" basket, comparison Auchan scored the most expensive, and Cora the most favorable.
Our calculations have shown that Cora has increased the prices in the "Napi" shopping basket by 15% compared to last year's Christmas prices, while Tesco and Auchan each increased by 18%.
The difference between the cheapest shopping basket of the previous year and the most expensive one of the current year was 12%, while the increase between the cheapest shopping basket of the past year and the most expensive one of the current year was 21%.
The average price increase was HUF 1,480.00.
The average price increase in the previous year was still 1,206.00 forints, but the VAT increase made itself felt in the prices at last Christmas.
Exactly this process hit the retail trade badly: Apparently the department stores could not really decide, which price range they should use with the individual articles, since the effects of the price increase were unforeseeable on the consumer behavior.
(If the trader badly plans the speed of circulation of a product, he may fall by substantial profits in the price range, which depends on the traffic intensity.)
Due to VAT, the inflation of the "Napi" shopping basket in the past year was so radical that the most expensive basket exceeded the value of 2006 by 1720 HUF, whereas the price difference for the cheapest basket was only 844 HUF.
This year, such extremes were not observed, as the most expensive basket cost 1,630.00 forints more than the previous year, and even the cheapest one saw a price increase of 1,284.00 forints.
In the comparison of the last two Christmas seasons, a catastrophic price increase became apparent, the price of the daily consumables in the hypermarkets rose in less than 20 months by more than 30 per cent.
(This, in turn, does not necessarily corroborate the data from the Central Statistical Office of Hungary: for some staple foods, the Statistical Office recorded a more than 30% inflation rate over a 12-month period.
For example, flour and eggs.)
However, if you take a look at the "Napi" shopping basket, this seems almost impossible with the latter, since the price level of the product, which was already expensive last year, has risen by hardly more than 10 percent, even in the worst case.
Obviously, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers - after all, they were able to pass the drastic price increase on to the multinationals.
In the golden trading triangle, the hypermarkets do not complain. It is continuously reported of good years.
Our experience shows that the majority of customers in the three department stores no longer pay any attention to prices.
Large quantities are bought from everything, durable food goes into pallets over the counter.
On Wednesday morning, there were endless queues at the cash desk in all three department stores, when suddenly the number of customers exploded.
However, the country reports a lower customer frequency, so many multinationals complain to pollsters that they cannot even achieve the planned turnover, not only for food, but also for sustainable consumer goods.
In many places, disinfectants are saved
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
Hygienic conditions in hospitals, overcrowding of beds, overburdening of staff - these are all factors that are not conducive to the control of infections, according to the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
The Traumatology Department of János Hospital has recently diagnosed an MRSA infection.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient admitted to hospital after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection.
The injured man from a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but shortly afterwards the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation could not be performed since then because of the bacterium, which is still in the body of the patient.
Until 10 December this year, 1,094 multidrug-induced infections from hospitals were reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to Karolina Böröcz, senior physician at the National Epidemiology Centre.
So many infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, but the number of unreported cases is likely to be higher.
Approximately two-thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin or oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about one third of the people in its nose without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as sore throat, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the doses are too high or if they are used improperly, the well-responding bacteria produce antibiotics which are resistant, and under appropriate conditions spread rapidly in hospitals.
Particularly in patients with weakened or permanently poorly functioning immune systems, but also in older patients or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents belong to the everyday life of the sick house.
One must not confuse the infection with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA does not exist only where it is not searched for.
Antibiotic resistance
"Such patients are isolated, nursing staff wear rubber gloves and masks for care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Although patients are examined for MRSA when they are admitted to hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rarely
The majority of the infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, however, the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable for the control of the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and old people ’ s homes, the hospitals should examine the imported patients and isolate the infected patients immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is less common in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no subsidies from the state health insurance for this investigation.
According to the medical director of the epidemiology centre, most cases would not come to light until the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also directives in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations are necessary in order to prevent resistance to the remedy, although this directive is not always adhered to by hospitals.
According to Karolina Böröcz, microbiological sampling is even rarer among outpatient or primary care patients.
Is Gespart with the disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transferred from one patient to another by nurses.
That is precisely why washing hands or wearing gloves and masks is so important, but there are also considerable shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in the domestic hospitals it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are even often overcrowded, the beds just lined up, although there should be an epidemiological distance between them of at least 1.5 meters.
As Karolina Böröcz notes further, it unfortunately happens in the financially less well placed hospitals that disinfectants are being saved, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that almost promote the development of infections.
Such infections have been shown to be far less common there, and the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are adhered to, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes enormous costs for health insurance companies, so they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA or its containment was recorded in the government programme.
According to first indications, the program is successful - as published data shows, the tendency of MRSA to infections in England is decreasing.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has made the prevention of the emergence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (including MRSA), as well as the prevention of infections in hospitals, one of its priorities.
Death-thrower, police chief was not drunk
In the case of the fatal car accident caused by the police chief of the XXII district, the official report is now available.
The now retired chief of police of the XXII district, who killed a pedestrian in a car accident on Tuesday, was neither alcoholized nor under the influence of drugs, said Attila Morvai, the press spokesman of the Budapest High Prosecutor's Office on Friday after the official report on the case was presented.
The report confirmed the results of the initial investigation, according to which the chief of police had not consumed alcohol before he took the wheel.
The former chief of police turned into Kossuth Lajos Street with his own car in the XXII district and ran over a 55 year old man who crossed the street at an unmarked place.
(According to StVO, however, this is not a mitigating circumstance - the handlebar has, even if pedestrians do not cross the street at the zebra crossing, inferior rank.)
The pedestrian died of his injuries after being admitted to the hospital.
According to police reports, the driver suffered a shock, then retired from his duties.
The Budapest prosecutor ’ s office has opened its investigation into the incident.
In addition, Attila Morvai mentioned that the former police chief had cooperated with the investigators from the outset.
Further EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three loan agreements totalling EUR 400 million in Budapest on Friday, with the aim of supporting education, transport and environmental protection, infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework for the financing of transport and environmental projects to be implemented with Cohesion Fund grants. Previously, the EUR 100 million loan agreement was signed, and the current agreement concerns the use of the EUR 200 million loan.
The sum of EUR 150 million agreed in the loan contract will also be used for the budgetary financing of educational projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for this purpose for Hungary; the remaining EUR 150 million will be used later in the context of the extension of the loan agreement.
In the field of innovation, the contracting parties have signed a EUR 50 million agreement, which will mainly be invested in research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
At the meeting, the subway line 4 was also discussed.
It has been agreed that once Hungary has clarified the details of the U-Bahn financing with the EU, the original contract and possible modifications will be discussed again.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects totalling EUR 8.4 billion in Hungary.
Interest rates are fixed at EURIBOR and the loan is provided by the EIB with an 8-year grace period and without any commission.
Bulgaria, the EU ’ s real estate paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - the whole of Europe is paying close attention to the previously seldom mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who buys what is still the cheapest market in the EU but is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re / Max Division.
Bulgaria is currently without a doubt the most sought-after place for property purchases in Eastern Europe, with affordable ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Between the mountains the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar are the most popular, but properties around Kavarna and Balcik are also increasingly in demand.
According to estimates of Re / Max analysts in Bulgaria, sooner or later the interior of the country will also attract investors, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and the exceptionally favorable region of Ruse will also see more buyers.
The capital city of Sofia also offers tempting offers - commercial and office space offer the highest returns.
Bulgaria is well on the way to becoming one of the most attractive European golfers ’ paradise, attracting tourists not only in the summer and winter seasons, but also in the other two seasons.
As a result, prospective investors are already buying on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying property in Bulgaria are also seeking to change their way of life.
Most buyers are English, but there are also potential buyers from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while in the Black Sea and ski resorts there are mainly Russian buyers.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re / Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle buy either revitalized properties for 50 100,000 euros, or run-down houses for 5 thousand euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connection and accessibility as well as communication possibilities are important, but also the proximity to a big city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
To the second category belong those, which are on the search for a vacation domicile (Bulgaria was listed in December among the Top Ten vacation destinations of the Germans).
The third group consists of businessmen who invest with the aim of increasing their value in the medium to long term.
Real estate in the capital is constantly getting more expensive, due to the ever-growing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but in the last five years prices have increased by 21% annually.
The rise in house prices far exceeds the rise in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced that the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and that the debate on the international climate, post-2012 regime, will continue on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali roadmap, which sets out the emissions-reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the expiry of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a fierce debate between developed and developing countries.
The US has already signaled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but would be willing to reduce greenhouse-gas emissions by 25% by 2020 compared to 1990 levels.
The other big question at the conference is whether the developed countries are prepared to support the developing countries both financially and technologically, in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement has also been reached on assistance to developing countries.
The Adaptation Fund, which is subordinated to the Kyoto Protocol, is to be administered by a 16 member council, probably at the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be read in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's 6%
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leadership in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that by 2020, the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% (compared to 1990 levels), regardless of whether or not the "post-2012 agreement" would be achieved successfully, and that the Union would even be ready to commit to a 30% reduction, while other major industrialised and developing countries would also be willing to fulfil their obligations with vigour and responsibility.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the target set by the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2%, whereas the EU, with its then 15 member states, had already committed itself to a reduction of 8%.
The target for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to 1985, which the country will certainly meet, as can be read in the Environment Ministry press release.
The stakes are high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be ready within two years, otherwise it would certainly only enter into force after 2012. In this case, the reduction plans laid down in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed by a new, international emission reduction system, the importance of which is also underlined by the IPCC, the international scientific climate change committee of the UN, which was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize, in its latest report.
This would delay emission reductions and make it unavoidable to increase the Earth's average temperature by more than 2 ° C, with extremely serious and irreparable consequences, according to scientists.
British army advertises on YouTube
Units of the British army have published recordings of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
The British Air Force (RAF) first discovered YouTube: since March 2006, special forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations conducted against the Taliban into the Internet, reports the BBC.
The images, which are shot with miniature cameras mounted on helmets, are checked at the air base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are posted on the Internet.
Unavoidable political message
Soldiers of the Luftwaffe have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" was viewed more than 75.000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 to publish videos of Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the British Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeeping forces stationed in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defence says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual objectives of the foreign missions.
Such published propaganda is almost free of charge compared to conventional television commercials, defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message, since they confirm the justification for the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans Advertise With game
But the army also has to fight against amateur recordings which, in addition to the carefully processed, censored recordings, also make it onto the net - such as those which show the death of the soldiers: In the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, at most, the losses are talked about, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
By the way, numerous videos of the war theatres in Iraq and Afghanistan have already been uploaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "genre" for themselves.
The Americans advertise in the somewhat different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the skin of the soldier in a more or less lifelike simulation.
