More and more forces mobilized for giant strike
The League of Trade Unions and the Hungarian Trade Union Federation will form their coordinating committee on Friday for the indefinite strike beginning on Monday.
A large protest meeting will be held on Saturday, and on Monday - the day of the referendum on the Health Insurance Act - the work stoppage will begin.
It is expected that there will be considerable traffic disruptions due to strikes, as rail traffic will be almost completely discontinued, and the Budapest Public Transport Company (BKV) will also strike until 1 pm.
Details of Monday's strike will be announced on Friday afternoon by the League of Trade Unions and the Federation of Trade Unions.
A LIGA - MOSZ strike committee is also established, which is responsible for coordinating the actions on Monday.
A large protest meeting will be held on Saturday, and from Monday, all organizations that have joined the strike will stop working indefinitely unless an agreement is reached with the government.
In other words, the end of the strike that began on the day of the parliamentary vote on the Health Insurance Act has not been defined.
If the National Council does not accept the Health Insurance Act, the unions immediately withdraw the call for a strike.
However, if the law is passed, the strike committees meet to discuss the way forward.
On the basis of the agenda of the National Council on Monday, it is even conceivable that the vote on the Health Insurance Act will not take place until later in the evening, or even until midnight.
Due to the strikes that will begin on Monday, traffic will be severely disrupted: the railwaymen will leave their jobs indefinitely, most of the public transport will stop in the morning, and more than half of the companies will stop working.
At the same time, there will be one-way highway blocks in many places.
Numerous trade unions and civil organisations have responded to the call for a strike - the list of participants is constantly updated on the League website.
Some organisations have announced strikes for an indefinite period, while others are planning a temporary work stoppage.
Until Thursday afternoon, the Hungarian Railways (MÁV) and the Free Railway Union (VDSZSZ) were unable to reach an agreement on sufficient benefits, even though more and more people are travelling by train during the Christmas holidays.
According to previous reports, the BKV will be on strike from the start of operations until 1 p.m., at Budapest Airport between 7 a.m. and 9 a.m., the LIGA trade unions for electricity and heat energy will stop their work for four hours, and the teachers' union and the Democratic Teachers' Union have called for two or two eight-hour strikes.
The Hungarian Medical Association is on strike on a country-wide basis, alternating at different times. The EDDSZ, the Democratic Trade Union of Health and Social Workers, a sub-organisation of the SZEF, the Forum for Trade Union Cooperation, is holding a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four points demanded by the League is that the government should withdraw the draft reform of health insurance and propose a new conception of social discourse.
The second requirement relates to the gradual introduction of the new pension model, which will become due from next year.
Requirement number three is that the qualifying professions should have access to the early retirement scheme before 2010.
The fourth point is that the VDSZSZ, which belongs to the League of Trade Unions, has not accepted the offer submitted by the Ministry of Transport concerning the secondary lines and is now calling for a new concept.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded this August with the support of the Movement for a Better Hungary, have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
The Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states, among other things: In connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "intensification of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic conflicts in the short term."
According to the research institute, the main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at provoking such a dispute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of political leaders: "Public figures have left the discussion of the Roma" question to representatives of radical political groups, who have now based their political strategy on the Roma "Hungary" opposition ".
It is thought that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favor extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent confrontation.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention paid by the domestic and foreign media, have "seriously damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
Let us remember: Since autumn 2006, the reorganization of radical and extreme right-wing groups in Hungary has been on a continuous upswing, so that since summer 2007, several organizations calling themselves "National Self-Defense Association" have been founded.
"What these groups have in common is that they each define themselves as a civil organisation, while they openly boast of preparing their members for defence tasks (civil protection, national defence, law enforcement), sometimes armed, citing the incompetence of the police, the army, or the state itself," they said.
And again: all this is happening according to the method that tries to camouflage as a bourgeois initiative various political aspirations based on the political and party moroseness of the population.
The emphasis on the civil character and the association form do not serve thus only the evasion of legal hurdles, which could emerge in the course of the registration with court - it is at the same time a political strategy.
The analysis shows that the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, and some ultra-nationalist politicians in certain neighbouring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as confirmation of their own anti-Hungarian policy.
All this has an impact on the political stability of the region "- they said.
From the point of view of the research institute, the founding of the Hungarian Guard is not a single phenomenon in Central Eastern Europe, so the political risk for the entire region has increased.
As reported, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose establishment was announced by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU) in August 2007.
In the background of the emergence of the Bulgarian Guard stood the Roma, a mass outcry that took place in one of the districts of Sofia (Krasna Polyana).
