Banks want to overcome crisis
The United States Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Great Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together against the crisis in the financial markets.
More than $100 billion will enter the currency markets through auctions.
At these auctions, banks auction interest rates at which they are willing to lend to each other.
For example, the US Fed is sending $40 billion to auction, and it is making another 24 easy for the European and Swiss central banks.
After the attacks of September 11, this is the first time that the central banks of the individual states have agreed on such a coordinated approach to avert or mitigate the consequences of a financial crisis.
"This step is intended to eliminate the main difficulties facing the economy, i.e. the increasing lack of freely available capital that banks can lend," wrote Bernard Baumohl of the consultancy firm Economic Outlook Group in a report for his clients.
"The coordinated action by central banks has reduced the likelihood of a US recession from 65% to around 50%," Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion on unused loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect further losses of billions.
"Central banks must have been really afraid of all the things they could do when they decided to do this," said ABN Amro Chief Economist Kieran Davies.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he continued.
Central banks fear that if the banks themselves have difficulty accessing bonds, loans will become more expensive for their customers.
That would reduce consumption and plunge the American economy into recession, possibly with an impact on economic growth around the world.
After failing to lower the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank interest rate used for lending money between banks, central banks have decided to do so.
This means that banks were constantly afraid to lend to each other, even though central banks in the US, Canada, and the UK had lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
"This will have the same effect as a further lowering of interest rates," said Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting of Reuters.
Some analysts believe that this move by central banks is helping to heat up the crisis, because it does not solve the fundamental problem, namely the fall of the US housing market.
