600,000 people failed to exchange their driver's license
600,000 motorists missed the deadline to exchange their old driving licence, which expires at the end of the year.
Today is the last day to apply for the exchange, so that the authorities can manage to issue a new driving licence by the end of the year.
However, the ministry does not fear that after New Year, hundreds of thousands of drivers without valid driving rights will take to the roads.
According to the authorities, it is mainly those who do not want to drive that have not exchanged their licence.
While small towns report a sharp drop in interest in exchanging tickets, the offices of the capital are showered with applications, and interest in exchanging tickets grew this week.
The city administration handles around 2000 customers a day.
You have to queue for about half an hour.
In Prague, some 140,000 drivers have not yet exchanged their driving licences.
The issuing of a new driving license lasts 20 days.
But it is possible to apply for the exhibition with a shortened period of five days.
In this case the driver has to pay 500 crowns.
Drivers who fail to complete the compulsory exchange by the end of the year and start driving without a valid driving licence will face a fine from January onwards.
The perpetrator pays a maximum of SEK 2,000.
The police can, however, leave it at transgression with an admonition.
In case of transgression, the penalty may rise to 2500 crowns.
According to earlier information, anyone who does not drive at all can also be punished by the municipality.
He could, it was said, be punished with even 30,000 crowns.
The ministry already called on the authorities to show leniency and to impose a fine of no more than 1,000 crowns.
According to the spokesman of the Ministry of Transport, Karel Hanzelka, nobody is to be punished with a thousand crowns.
The driving licence is a document for anyone to decide whether or not to possess it.
It is not an identity card that everyone must have, a valid one at that.
People who no longer want to drive should hand in their driving licence.
It is sufficient to take him to the competent municipal office or to send him there by registered mail.
At the end of the year, driving licences issued between 1964 and 1993 become invalid.
However, drivers will also gradually have to exchange other types of driving licences.
People with driving licences from 1994 to 2000 still have three years to exchange.
The validity of licences issued from 2001 to 2004 ends in December 2013.
According to Hanzelka, this is about 2.6 million more licences.
