Cuba - most beautiful island of the Caribbean
For visitors, it really is an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday will be fulfilled if you just choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is calm like a pond.
Palm trees and all inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and beguiling cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this in abundance.
But only on one island you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Greater Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place ever seen by a human eye.
Havana once became a camp or transit camp of treasures stolen by the Spaniards in America and then transported to Europe.
And then came the American epoch.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the bosses of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the USA (especially during the prohibition) was welcomed and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra
In Havana, skyscrapers grew, cars drove across the broad boulevards, which were among the cult symbols of the 1950s.
Ernest Hemingway bought an estate in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and he had his yacht in Cojímar.
Stars of show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
And today?
You can also leave your autograph on the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana.
At the bar of the Hotel Nacional, you can mix your own cocktails.
And the cult cars of the fifties still circulate in Havana today, because the formerly imported Schigulis and Fiats have long since fallen apart in the salty and humid air.
Havana, especially its oldest part, may have been badly run down, nowhere else in the area can you find so many wonderful colonial sights as here.
Other places are being cleaned up, for example Trinidad.
With regard to the fact that tourism brings urgently needed money, there was green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have been built not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín and on islets such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a quirk that is unique in the world and attracts especially railway lovers.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam and diesel-powered narrow gauge railways to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see cute and fully functioning locomotives, whose contemporaries are elsewhere long since in the museum.
Excursion destinations
The majority of visitors to Cuba do not miss out on the most important places.
So you do not have to write about Varadero or Havana in detail.
Just to mention that in the already mentioned Hemingway estate there is a museum, the visit of which should not be missed by those who like this writer.
The Viñales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on limestone.
The Mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities accumulated fertile soil, through which weathered rock areas are covered by dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form you can meet him when you visit one of the cigar factories of Havana.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the TV series "Major Zeman" was shot there.
Trinidad
An ancient city founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
The trade in slaves and sugar brought her fame and wealth.
The wealth was embodied in the beautiful beauty of the small town.
The Spanish colonial architecture, strongly influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed since four hundred years.
Trinidad, situated between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that in the 1950s there was no road connecting the area with the rest of the country.
This isolation contributed to the fact that it went unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was torn down, everyone was glad that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than one afternoon for Trinidad, then it is worth to visit interesting places in the area, such as the beach Playa Ancon or the "valley of the sugar factories".
In the evening you should then go to the Casa de la Música, which comes to life after dark, and where the music does not remain silent until the morning.
Baracoa
This small town in the far east of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful of the island.
To be sure, this view is also influenced by the path to achieving it.
Both roads, leading from Guantánamo, have to cross high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape that is hardly touched by human intervention.
This eastern outpost of Cuba was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List thanks to the untouched nature there.
It is the place where the best chocolate is made, where you can see the Columbus cross in the church (in fact, it was made about a hundred years after Columbus travelled), and from the hill where the former castle, now the Hotel El Castillo, stands, you can see several table mountains, the most famous of which is El Yunque.
About coffee, rum, cigars, Sierra Maestra, Bay of Pigs and Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana Cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion to which the descendants of slaves profess, about all this one could write many pages.
But, as they say, it is better to look at things with your own eyes.
