National debt will soar to a trillion in 2009
Each Czechs has a national debt of SEK 84,000.
The total debt rose to 842.7 billion crowns by the end of September.
The government had planned to go into debt with 159.2 billion cones this year.
At the beginning of December, however, thanks to the better development of government budgetary policy, the Ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion.
The national debt of the Czech Republic rose to 842.7 billion crowns by the end of September.
Within the first nine months of this year, they rose by 40.2 billion.
Since June, however, they have fallen by 13.4 billion.
The Ministry of Finance thus confirmed its information on government debt from the beginning of October.
A debt of 84,000 crowns is owed to each Czech.
Throughout the past year, the state has borrowed more than 111 billion crowns.
"So far, it seems that, thanks to the lower deficit for next year, we may not exceed the 1 trillion crowns limit until 2009.
