But I don't expect such a change, "he remarked.
Growing Debt
The national debt stems from the debt of the state government and comes mainly from the accumulation of budget deficits.
The national debt is financed by treasury bills, government bonds, direct bonds or, for example, bonds issued by the European Investment Bank.
Domestic public debt rose to 719.4 billion crowns this year.
The foreign debt of the state increased by 1.7 billion crowns to 123.3 billion.
The so-called marketable national debt reached 803.3 billion crowns at the end of September and has fallen by 13.7 billion since June.
The average maturity of public debt rose to 6.5 years.
"The total debt increased by 13 percent over the year from the first to the third quarter, which is really a lot given how well the economy is doing.
It is interesting to note that the growth is mainly in bonds, where the increase is 20%.
It is bad that the debt is rising, but on the other hand it shows that something can be done before the pension reform comes, "Pikora commented on the data.
Better than expected
The financing strategy and the handling of the public debt for 2007 indicates that the government had planned to raise 159.2 billion crowns for this year.
At the beginning of December, however, thanks to the better development of state budgetary policy, the Ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion crowns.
This amount comes mainly from the state budget deficit, which this year will apparently reach SEK 76 billion instead of the estimated EUR 91.3 billion.
Furthermore, the maximum planned appropriations for the Consolidation Agency amount to CZK 13.3 billion, a ten billion reserve for paying pensions, the financing of government bonds amounting to EUR 43 billion and instalments for loans to the European Investment Bank amounting to EUR 1.8 billion.
She was brought before a court in Khartoum today for giving a teddy bear a name.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who had been accused of insulting Islam in Sudan, was sentenced by a court in Khartoum on Thursday evening to 15 days ’ imprisonment and subsequent expulsion.
The British woman was accused of having allowed six- to seven-year-old students to give a teddy bear the name Mahomet, although any depiction of the Islamic prophet is prohibited.
It deserved to be flogged.
After several complaints from parents of pupils to the Sudanese Ministry of Culture, the 54-year-old primary school teacher, who worked at Unity High School in Khartoum, was picked up at her home on Sunday and accused of insulting Islam under Article 125 of the Sudanese Criminal Code.
In fact, this affair began in September, when the teacher asked her six- to seven-year-old students to choose a name for the class teddy bear.
The children propose eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed, reports headmaster Robert Boules.
Finally, when the class votes, 20 out of 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite first name.
To be sure, Mohammed is the name of the Islamic prophet, but especially a very common first name in Sudan.
Afterwards the children made a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the caption My name is Mohammed.
The bear himself did not carry a sign bearing that name, but the problem is quite simple: the depiction of the Islamic prophet is seen as an insult to Islam.
One of the Muslim colleagues of Gillian Gibbons, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, said that he knew her well and that she had never done anything to offend a religious faith, but I am sorry that she asked the children to vote for a name, in his opinion this is only an innocent mistake.
An opinion shared by many students of the teacher, who describe her as very attentive to their students and as a person who never talks about religion in class.
Consider that the first name Mohammed is also the second most common second name in Britain, with 14 different spellings in English.
This first name, often chosen by Muslim families, is considered a kind of homage to the Prophet (it is often given to the firstborn of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
Can we give it to a toy, for example?
This is, of course, a question of interpretation.
At the last negotiation meeting in Vienna on Wednesday, no agreement was reached on the future status of the province.
At the end of the failure
The Serbs and Albanians from Kosovo concluded a sixth and final discussion session on Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, without being able to overcome their controversies about the future status of the separatist province.
It is regrettable that the parties were unable to reach an agreement on the status, said European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger at a press conference in Vienna.
Emphasising that peace in the region was at stake, Frank Wilsner called on Belgrade and Pristina to fulfil their obligations to maintain peace and to continue the talks beyond the end of the negotiations.
No violence is expected in the immediate future, but we are at the beginning of a very difficult period, he added, and indicated that there are significant tensions.
End of conciliations on 10 December
The mediators of the Troika, which unites the European Union, the USA and Russia, will meet for the last time in Serbia and Kosovo on Monday.
The future of the province, which is inhabited by 90% Albanian speakers, could become clearer if Ischinger, Wilsner and the Russian mediator Alexander Botsane are to submit their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and last negotiation session since the Troika was mandated by the UN last August to negotiate a new mediation.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation mandate to end on December 10.
The Russians, who had already blocked the granting of Kosovo ’ s independence to the Security Council, insist on continuing negotiations beyond that end date.
Russia has been, and remains, an advocate of a negotiated solution, a consensual solution, said Mr Khartchenko.
Unilateral Declaration of Independence?
After Kosovo has been under UN administration for eight years, Western countries believe that independence under EU supervision is the only solution for the future.
Pristina is ready to declare them unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in their favor.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy
Unfortunately, no agreement could be reached, the President of the Autonomous Authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, announced at the hotel in Baden, where since Monday these negotiations of the last chance have been conducted.
Hashim Thaci, former leader of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, shared his regret.
However, he added that the autonomy plan proposed by Belgrade belongs to a past that has led to killings and deportations.
