These negotiations have lasted two years.
They must end as they began: in the Security Council.
In response to the journalists, Fatmir Sejdiu said that the Kosovo Parliament would have the final say on the status, adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by the Albanian-speaking population would be carried out in coordination with Western countries.
Bush elicits agreement between Israelis and Palestinians
At the opening of the international peace conference, which met on Tuesday under his leadership in Annapolis, Maryland, President Bush announced that Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed on a joint declaration.
He also said that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to start negotiations immediately to find a final settlement to the 60-year-old dispute between their two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, Bush promised that he would do all he could to help them conclude a peace treaty before the end of 2008.
In the meantime, the Palestinians must destroy terrorist infrastructures, and Israel must cease its colonization, Bush said, reminding the two parties of their commitments to the Roadmap for Peace that they agreed to in 2003.
The head of the White House stressed that the negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian Authority under Abbas were ultimately aimed at a peace agreement that would resolve all outstanding issues without exception, including the key issues.
This term encompasses the three serious issues that are at the heart of the disputes between Israelis and Palestinians: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem, and the fate of the Arab refugees displaced by the 1948 conflict from their homes in what is now the State of Israel.
After the American President, Abbas took the floor and insisted that the forthcoming negotiations be conducted in a comprehensive and thorough manner and provide a settlement on all points, enumerating, among others, Jerusalem, the refugees, the borders, the colonies, water and security.
When Olmert, for his part, took the floor, he committed himself to ensuring that the forthcoming ceasefire negotiations would be conducted directly and without interruption and that he would endeavour to bring them to an end before the end of 2008.
Bush has set the deadline for the implementation of his vision of two juxtaposed states, one Palestinian and one Israeli, for the end of 2008.
Saudi Arabia has disclosed that it received a Bush pledge in this sense from Bush before deciding to attend the conference.
Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis is a great success for Washington, has launched a plan adopted by all Arab countries to offer Israel peace, in exchange for its withdrawal from all Arab territories occupied during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
Annapolis marks a crossroads in the history of the Middle East, particularly because it attacks the roots of the conflict and its central aspects, the Saudi Arabian prince said in an interview with the Arabic-language daily, which is funded by Saudi money.
