Spectacular repair on the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his comrades from the crew of the International Space Station (ISS) will have taken more than seven hours in space to carry out the spectacular repair of a defective solar collector, which is indispensable for the continuation of scientific work on the station.
A daring exit that has set several records due to its duration, the distance from habitable modules, the speed with which it was organised and the tools made by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem arose on Wednesday, when the astronauts unloaded the Harmony module from the Discovery space shuttle, a large cylindrical section that will soon house the European and Japanese scientific laboratories.
This module is a kind of landing bridge for the module "Laboratories".
But they must be able to be supplied with electricity.
The second task of the crew was therefore to implement a 17.5-ton module for generating electricity via solar panels, which was already on board the ISS, in order to bring it into its final position.
After moving it, the crew started to restructure the solar panels of the module, whose span is 76 meters.
And it happened that one of the collectors, which can be folded like accordions, was damaged by a jammed cable on a length of about one meter
The restructuring was stopped in order not to damage the collector even more.
The astronauts, who were originally supposed to leave the Discovery space shuttle for an inspection walk and then repair another solar collector whose rotation system was faulty, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was chosen to walk around at the end of the 30 meter long remote controlled arm of the space shuttle that had been attached to the station to carry out the repair.
He is one of NASA's best Spacewalkers.
Large, resistant, very skillful, he has a well developed torso and long arms.
The 46-year-old trained doctor was thus chosen to operate the injured solar collector.
After examining the damage, he cut the faulty cable and attached a kind of rail to the damaged spot.
He was assisted by a second Spacewalker who remained near the lock, and, inside, by the other astronauts, including Peggy Whitson, commander of the crew.
The tool he used, a mini hockey stick wrapped in an insulator to prevent an electric shock on the solar panels, which generate several hundred volts, was invented and constructed by the astronauts on board the station.
When the operation was over, Scott Parazynski waited until the collector was fully unfolded before counting his tools and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed half a day of relaxation before seven astronauts returned to the Discovery space shuttle today, presumably for Wednesday's return flight to Earth.
