A heavy souvenir
After being treated confidentially for more than 60 years, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed over a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, could not be consulted until now, except with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individually and name-related, i.e. when consulted by a former victim or his relatives.
The eleven states in charge of its administration, including Germany, France, Israel and the USA, agreed in May 2006 to make it accessible to researchers and historians.
Once the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening-up took effect yesterday.
Delicate information
Historians ’ access to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to investigate, above all, the deportation of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the state of health of the forced laborers, explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives, which are administered by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as alleged homosexuality or the intellectual disability of some victims of deportation.
The prisoner lists of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest, thus paving the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of personal inquiries in Bad Arolsen.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
One must not expect anything fundamentally new in these documents, Pr. Wolfgang Benz, director of the research center for anti-Semitism of the technical University of Berlin, had explained 2006.
The EU and India want a free trade agreement in 2008.
Mutual trade between India and Europe currently stands at around EUR 60 billion a year.
The EU is India's main trading partner, accounting for 18% of its external trade.
European Trade Minister Peter Mandelson and his Indian counterpart, Kamal Nath, said that the European Union and India hope to sign a free trade agreement in 2008.
Last April, EU Foreign Ministers gave the green light to the European Commission to open negotiations with a view to signing Free Trade Agreements (FTA) with India, South Korea and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (Asean). Mutual trade between India and Europe is already worth some 60 billion euros a year.
The EU is India's first trading partner and accounts for 18% of its external trade.
The EU is also its first foreign investor, but according to European Commission figures, India is only the EU's ninth trading partner.
A free-trade pact will take the two economies forward enormously, and India would improve its access to a market of 450 million wealthy Europeans, Peter Mandelson confirmed.
Europe is the first or second market for the ten most frequently exported products by India, added the European Commissioner. Asian and European giants exchange 47 billion euros worth of goods and 10 billion euros worth of services every year, said Daniéle Smadja, Chair of the European Commission ’ s Delegation in New Delhi this week, regretting that reciprocal trade has not yet reached its potential. EU and India are meeting on Friday for their eighth diplomatic meeting in New Delhi, where Prime Minister Manmohan Singh and European Commission President José Manuel Durao Barrosso will be present.
