The Bank of England takes note of the concern and offers £10 billion for five weeks
The Bank of England expressed concern on Thursday to contain the current recurrent anxiety about the terms of the loan and announced an offer of £10 billion at a 5.75% base rate for five weeks, an offer with an unusual maturity.
In order to allay fears that conditions in the financial market will be particularly harsh at the end of the year, and to give banks greater certainty about the way in which they are to organise their liquidity positions during this period, the bank intends to offer a significant proportion of its savings during the maintenance phase, which begins on 6 December, in the form of an open market for five weeks, it states in a communication.
The bank further explains that in this way on 6 December at 12.15 GMT 10 billion pounds (14 billion euros) will be put into circulation, at the real estate tax rate and only until 10 January.
This is apparently the first time that the BoE has put liquidity into circulation for five weeks in an open markets operation.
This usually happens for a week.
In its communication, the BoE adds that it stands ready to take further measures to maintain the day-to-day differentiation of interest rates on interbank loans at its basic interest rate.
The day-to-day differential between banks was 5.829% on Wednesday.
The three-month interest rate has stabilised at 6.6%, slightly higher since 18 September.
Since the start of the financial crisis last summer, the sums put into circulation by the Bank of England have been linked to fines that had dissuaded banks from drawing them.
According to certain rumours, reinforced by the development of the pound exchange rate in contrast to the euro, many preferred to sign for the sums put into circulation by the European Central Bank, at more advantageous interest rates and with more discretion.
