The Congress approves the MIFID Directive, which entered into force on 1 November.
Parallel to the parliamentary drafting, which ended today with the Senate vote on the project ’ s supplementary / amendments, the Government published the provisions resulting from the new law with the intention of allowing the entry into force of both provisions by the end of the year.
The representatives of the various companies unanimously praised the efforts of the members of the Congress and the Senate who, in their negotiations and votes, had aimed at establishing the best possible regulation that would guarantee the security of investors and regulate the activities of individual entrepreneurs in order to guarantee a generally efficient market.
In addition to modernising the financial markets, MIFID, which is redefining the investment services regulations, is pursuing an improvement in investor protection, increasing the control rights of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive will enable financial advice to be provided both to specialised firms and to natural or legal persons, and will also contribute to the establishment of new financial services firms (ESIS), the advisory firms which will be merged with investment and securities brokerage firms.
Furthermore, it expands the number of systems for executing financial transactions, adding to the regulated circulation markets the multilateral systems for securities transactions and the systems for internationalising trading orders, which would eventually compete with the current economic players.
The law obliges investment companies to disclose the focal points of their company profile, the confrontation and forms of risk management in the market and to register all the projects carried out in order to facilitate the CNMV ’ s control task.
In retrospect, the Congressional Economic Commission made provision for further changes, with the decision that the titled bond must now be considered as a complex financial resource for the investor due to its high level of risk confirmed by the US mortgage and banking crisis (US Mortgage Crisis).
