New fears over gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is brewing between Ukraine and Russia, increasing the risk that Russian fuel exports to Western Europe will be affected.
Most of Russia ’ s gas exports to the European Union (EU) pass through Ukraine, and any dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
An earlier conflict between the two states last year reduced deliveries to the EU.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes at a time when the Ukrainian government and Russia ’ s state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be billed more, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for Gazprom ’ s imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks," Anatoly Kinakh, Minister of Economy of Ukraine, told Reuters.
"The changing gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit charges [to Western Europe] via Ukraine."
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut deliveries to Ukraine.
As a result, exports to Western Europe have fallen, driving up prices sharply.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world ’ s largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom is replenishing its own supplies of gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
