He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video broadcast at the Old Bailey in October and was charged in connection with the alleged car bomb attack in Great Britain.
It is expected that the State Health Service will carry out checks prior to the appointment of foreign staff to ensure that they have the qualifications, experience and authorisations required to work in the UK.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to verify criminal records, the Agency does not have jurisdiction to obtain this information outside the UK.
The main auditor ’ s report now states, among other recommendations, that the board should take up guidelines from the criminal record extract, which helps employers with inspections in different countries.
"Although we found evidence of these controls in some personnel documents, they were not routinely carried out," the report noted.
Black said the Scottish health authorities would follow their investigative guidelines to a large extent prior to recruitment, but added: "Our report identifies areas where the system can be improved to ensure accurate information on the number of foreign health workers is available."
BMA Scotland ’ s Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was “extremely unlikely ” that pre-employment investigations of potential NHS staff would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
