The climate on Venus may give a glimpse of the future of the Earth
Venus was perhaps once a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft in orbit show that the planet resembles a distant twin of the Earth even more than was previously known.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbour to Earth.
The two worlds are about the same size and have similar planetary orbits, but Venus is closer to the Sun.
Billions of years ago, Venus would have had conditions very similar to those on Earth and could even have been habitable, scientists now believe.
But because of the unchecked carbon dioxide, the greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by solar radiation, and a slower rate of rotation, Venus embarked on a completely different course of development.
Today, the planet is stripped of water and has a surface temperature that is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricanes, strong winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency ’ s Venus Express spacecraft, which examined the planet for a year, offer a sobering view of how the Earth could develop in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at Oxford University, one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said, "It is clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, while the planets are otherwise quite similar."
"Our new data make it possible to construct a scenario in which Venus began billions of years ago like Earth, possibly with an inhabitable environment."
