Labour Pain
Gordon Brown has discovered yet another pit to fall into; his way out of it remains the same.
For British scandals, it is not particularly slippery.
No noble titles seem to have been sold, no politician ’ s Paris hotel bills paid, no extramarital toes sucked.
But the revelation that a wealthy businessman has disguised donations to Britain ’ s ruling Labour Party for more than £650,000 ($1.3 million) over four years under other people ’ s names, and that the party has failed to report this, is something that the embattled Gordon Brown would have done well without.
When, two months ago, the prime minister evaded the call for an election, stupidly insulting the British intelligentsia by claiming that opinion polls did not influence that decision, there was hope that he would provide a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly astute leader of Liberal Democrats, put it, the once-dreaded Brown has gone from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The clumsy rescue of Northern Rock, a ailing bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Poorly thought-out proposals to amend tax laws have turned business associations against the government.
The fiscal loss of personal data of 25 million people revealed unimaginable administrative bungling.
A trio of retired generals launched an Upper House uprising in protest at cuts in military spending: being a minister of the armed forces, they claimed, was a part-time job.
Now there are the many donations from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labor ’ s general secretary (and its former vicarious director) has already resigned.
None of this means that Brown is irrevocably headed for resignation.
Yet governments can reach a turning point after which they feel it impossible to govern.
People neither like nor trust politicians, but they usually restrain their skepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it is clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve the situation, and he does not even need to be there long, that delay is over: the civil service is beginning to leak; cabinet ministers are beginning to chat; the press is looking for bad news; and the government is becoming defensive and aimless.
In one way, Brown ’ s position is particularly difficult, because, unlike other leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he wanted to deny Tony Blair, he was his first lieutenant.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax records, for example, are linked to decisions taken by Brown as Chancellor of the Treasury.
And even if he was not directly involved in Blair ’ s misfortunes – as in the long “money-for-nobility ” investigation of political party funding – voters may assume that he was.
Still Brown ’ s situation is not quite as bad as she looks
The sins are not as terrible as the conservatives describe them.
As with Mr. Bean, no one died or was completely deceived.
And the antidote, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Brown ’ s naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid, and easily brutal government.
The new fuss about political donations is a good example.
The garboesque Abraham, who compares his donations with his charitable gifts, says he does not wish any public recognition for his benevolence.
That may be so, but it was not for him to decide.
The laws against anonymity for large political contributors are clear, and they exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who govern the country.
Watt, who says he knew about Abraham ’ s agreement, but not that it was illegal, will of course have to ask himself some questions; just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labor ’ s chief financier, who was told about the odd donations in October.
But, so far, Brown is not involved: there is nothing to suggest that he knew about these confusions, even though most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He quickly condemned the violation of the laws by his party, but he watered down this determination by grasping a known instrument, a committee of inquiry on the subject - led to make the full measure of a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the "lessons to be learned" are not very complicated.
If the law has been broken, it is a matter for the police.
Apart from that, there are other things that Mr Brown must do, such as finding a permanent chairman for the independent committee on standards in public life, which has been vacant for six months, and moving forward with a radical reform of political party funding.
That would require the Labour hardliners to cooperate with the Conservatives and eventually give up the special financial relationship with the trade unions - bitter pills for a party member like Mr Brown.
But he should be aware of some biased facts.
Conservatives now have clear leadership in opinion polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way he can achieve victory is through undeniable righteousness and solid competence.
Cardsharks
Is America ’ s Credit Card Market Contagious?
When blood is in the water, it is only natural that dorsal fins whirl around excitedly.
Now that America ’ s housing market is ailing, predators are targeting the country ’ s credit-card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts estimate that credit card losses could reach $99 billion if the contagion of underfunded loans spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both the deductions and the default rates, which measure the proportion of loans that are either not recoverable or are more than 30 days late.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken a $1.4 billion fee from its US consumer financing, in part due to the weakness of credit card holders.
It is still too early to panic.
Losses and delays are still low.
According to Moody, the third-quarter default rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in America ’ s private-insolvency laws in 2005 led to an abrupt fall in bankruptcy filings, which in turn accounted for a large part of the card losses; the number of filings (and thus default charges) would rise again, whether or not general conditions for borrowers deteriorate.
Industry also reports solid payment rates showing how much of its debt consumers pay off each month
and confidence in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the standstill in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of the TowerGroup, a research company, expects that the expenditure quantities for 2007 will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
Direct channels of infection between the housing credit crisis and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers are more likely to take up credit card debt now that home loans are drying up.
The card issuers, however, look at the cash flow instead of capital values, so falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the creditworthiness of the borrower.
They may even be advantageous for ticket issuers.
Incentives for consumers to continue paying mortgage rates decline when the value of the property is less than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important among repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also respond much more quickly and flexibly than lenders to the more stormy conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of assets.
“We will not wake up one day and completely reassess the loans, ” says Gary Perlin, Capital Ones Chief Financial Officer.
Even if a sudden shortfall in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained downturn are far more real.
If lower house prices and credit reduction push America into recession, industry will no doubt face a grimmer future.
Keep looking out for these shark fins.
