Venus is the infernal twin of Earth
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought: The European space probe "Venus Express" has detected lightning in the atmosphere and wind vortices at the poles, just like they occur on Earth in winter.
For almost three decades, scientists have suspected that it flashes on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided the evidence - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: The lightnings on Venus shoot from cloud to cloud at a height of about 56 kilometres, Christopher Russel from the University of California in Los Angeles reports in the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "primordial soup" theory, lightning created life on earth: thunderstorms are said to have stimulated reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there has ever been life there, it must have been in very early history," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is around a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees prevail.
"Venus may be the devil's twin of Earth, but it is a twin," said Russell.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has undergone such a completely different development, is the basic question of Esa ’ s mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as since the beginning of the nineties, no probe was used for the exploration of this planet.
According to the researchers, the latest research results, which are now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underline the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also show that the similarities between our neighbouring planet and Earth are greater than initially assumed," says Esa.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud vortex at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the terrestrial winter hemisphere, writes a research team headed by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and with a diameter of 12,100 kilometres is almost as large.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits the Sun in just under 225 days.
But it turns much slower around itself: A Venus day lasts 243 earth days.
Although Venus hardly resembles Earth with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, scientists assume that both planets formed under quite similar conditions.
On both sides water accumulated, which remained on earth in oceans, but was lost on Venus into space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed in carbonate rocks on Earth, it accounts for the majority of the atmosphere on Venus.
