These are not Warhol's boxes
Anyone who combines the terms Sweden and wooden box thinks of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol's catalogue raisonné.
Most of the ninety-four Brillo "Stockholm" boxes listed there are forgeries.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo "Boxes of 1968", internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm has now come to a sobering conclusion: The six "Brillo" Boxes, which the former museum director Pontus Hultén bequeathed to the Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - and probably the majority of the approximately one hundred other Brillo "Boxes of the Stockholm type", which are in circulation on the international art market.
The prehistory is nested, a confusing concatenation of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, in New York, Warhol created his first "Brillo" boxes, painted wooden boxes based on the red and blue and white design of the "Brillo" soap powder cardboard boxes.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 exhibited – with Warhol ’ s agreement – hundreds of Brillo ’ s boxes made of cardboard: these did not come from Warhol (for cost reasons), but were delivered directly from the Brillo ’ s cardboard factory.
They were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, in 1968, Warhol probably granted permission to produce a few Brillo ’ s wooden boxes in Sweden, but they were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which, at the time, were authorised as originals, and rightly entered into the history of art and auctions under the name "Stockholm Type".
Some of them have obtained more than 100 000 dollars at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that in 1968 about a hundred wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén ’ s 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, has examined the six museum owned Brillo ’ s boxes as well as three privately owned Swedish boxes, two of which were produced in 1968 in Stockholm: their pressboard panels were first primed and sanded, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the pressboard with a paint roller without primer - it is also not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo and Boxes," says Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not reach another conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies / exhibition material."
As early as July, however, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "serious allegations" raised about soap powders and boxes.
Since then, however, they have remained inexorably silent.
Rebellious soldiers in Manila give up
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers have given up hiding in a hotel in Manila, demanding the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
He could not answer for bloodshed, said leader Antonio Trillanes, who accused the president of corruption and election fraud, reporters at the hotel.
Previously, soldiers loyal to the government had stormed the hotel using tear gas.
The two dozen or so soldiers had been entrenched in the building for hours.
About half of them stood trial on Thursday because of a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He used the trial to suddenly break away with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police, who were supposed to guard him, had apparently defected to him and joined his mutiny.
They invaded the Peninsula and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal government troops closed off the area around the posh hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
The National Security Advisor, Norberto Gonzales, condemned the actions of the soldiers.
"People have had enough," Trillanes said.
"We call on people to join us."
General Danilo Lim, who previously commanded the elite unit of the Scout Rangers, said other army units wanted to join the march shortly.
Critics of the government had called for big demonstrations against the president on Friday.
Their government has been overshadowed for months by allegations of corruption.
Manila ’ s financial district was already the scene of the attempted mutiny of around 200 military personnel against Arroyo in 2003.
The uprising failed after almost 24 hours because of the army ’ s refusal to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven attempted coups against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
